## Plot methods

Many different objects in R have defined `plot` methods:


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
methods(plot)
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout}

```
 [1] plot.acf*            plot.data.frame*     plot.decomposed.ts* 
 [4] plot.default         plot.dendrogram*     plot.density*       
 [7] plot.ecdf            plot.factor*         plot.formula*       
[10] plot.function        plot.ggplot*         plot.gtable*        
[13] plot.hclust*         plot.histogram*      plot.HoltWinters*   
[16] plot.isoreg*         plot.lm*             plot.medpolish*     
[19] plot.mlm*            plot.pal_continuous* plot.pal_discrete*  
[22] plot.ppr*            plot.prcomp*         plot.princomp*      
[25] plot.profile*        plot.profile.nls*    plot.R6*            
[28] plot.raster*         plot.spec*           plot.stepfun        
[31] plot.stl*            plot.table*          plot.transform*     
[34] plot.ts              plot.tskernel*       plot.TukeyHSD*      
see '?methods' for accessing help and source code
```


:::
:::


e.g. if you call `plot` on an object of type `lm`, it will call `plot.lm`

## Linear model diagnostic fits


::: {.cell layout-align="center"}

```{.r .cell-code}
fit <- lm(bill_length_mm ~ bill_depth_mm, 
          data = penguins, subset = species == "Gentoo")

par(mfrow=c(2,2)) # see all four plots together
plot(fit)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](index_files/figure-revealjs/unnamed-chunk-9-1.png){fig-align='center' width=1200}
:::
:::


